To preface my poor review, I just want to say that I've previously had fairly pleasant experiences here while dining in. Unfortunately, I can't say the same for my experience today. I also never leave reviews for restaurants, but this one was more than warranted!  I selected the option that Sushi AOI was offering through a meal-pickup service today, which consisted of 6 California rolls and 6 spicy tuna rolls. The tuna had a gray color and slimy texture, which I know is not normal. Spicy tuna rolls are typically my favorite type of roll, and I order it quite frequently at various restaurants, so I know that the tuna itself is supposed to be a pinkish-red color and not gray. Moreover, tuna doesn’t usually have a ‘fishy’ taste, but this one did, which tells me that the fish was expired.  I've attached the picture of the spicy tuna rolls.  While the California rolls seemed fine, I was so put off by the bad tuna that I couldn’t finish my lunch and had to go out and buy something else. I'm so displeased by the spicy tuna today that I am very hesitant to dine here again. BEWARE OF THE GRAY TUNA!!!!!

Before my first time eating at Sushi AOI, I went there for happy hours twice. Both visits had a great time getting sake and beer (no food). My first time eating there was on 12/18/14, I got a California Roll and two salmon nigiri. For 4 days I've been going in and out of the restroom constantly. I know that with Sushi there is always a possibility of getting food poising but this is the first time it's happened to me. I also worked in a Sushi Restaurant all throughout college, ate there often, and never got food poisoning.  It will be tough for me to go and trust that the food is fresh after my initial visit but everyone else seems to enjoy it and I do enjoy their happy hour, so I'm leaving a 2 star review.

I've only been here for lunch and I've never been disappointed. If you are planning to go for lunch, order the Lunch Box. It comes with a California roll, edamame, miso soup, salad and rice. From there you have your choice of entree. Oder the Tofu Steak. You can thank me later.

This isn't a premium sushi spot by any means, but it's more than serviceable.  Prices aren't too out of line for the area, and happy hour cocktails and beers are well priced (though food selection is wan, with frozen calamari and skimpy rolls).  If you're looking for quality sushi, you might want to look elsewhere (it's not something DC is known for anyways). But for a lunch time meal or happy hour with friends after work, this place is a good option.
